Back to School:
The first day of school, August 17th, will be adjusted this year. The elementary school will be holding conferences from 11am-7pm instead of regular school. This will replace the open house that is usually scheduled prior to the first day of school.

The MS will have an Orientation from 8:10-11:00 am. This is for all students in grades 7&8. Route buses will run at the scheduled morning times and return students home again at 11:10 am instead of the normal first day of school due to the abrupt closure of school last year.

The The HS will have an Orientation from 12:45-3:10 pm. This is for all students in grades 9-12. Route buses will run at approximately 12:00 pm and return students home again at 3:10 pm instead of the normal first day of school due to the abrupt closure of school last year.

post_text:
1st Day of School & Professional Development for Teachers & Staff

The official start date of school is Monday, August 17, 2020. Here is a breakdown of the first day of school:

Elementary – Parent/Student conferences will be scheduled from 11:00-7:00.

Middle School – Orientation for grades 7-8 starting at 8:15-11:00 am

High School – Orientation for grades 9-12 starting at 12:45-3:15 pm

Teachers will have additional professional development opportunities prior to the beginning of school. New teachers will begin the morning of August 10 with returning teachers beginning in the afternoon on August 10. Additionally, many teachers have been taking courses offered through PAC and other educational agencies throughout the summer to assist in online and hybrid learning environments.

Have you started thinking about school starting in August? We have, and health safety is at the top of our list. We have already taken the following COVID-19 preparations:

• Sneeze guards have been installed at a number of locations.
• Plexiglas barriers are being installed at some other locations.
• Face shields for nurses or others
• Infrared thermometers
• Ordered backpack Electrostatic Disinfecting system for buses and school. (x2)
• UV-C room sanitizers (x3)
• We have hand sanitizer on hand (over 25 gallons)
• We have wipes on hand (over 12,650)
• Paper face masks (1500)

post_text:
PAC is closed through April 13th, classes would resume April 14th. This is the best case scenario, however, you should develop contingency plans at this time for what could be longer. PAC is continuing to monitor state and national events that are being canceled due to ongoing health concerns. This is a very fluid time, and all plans are based on the best available information at that time. Please understand that plans may continue to be modified as new information becomes available. We are continuing to take this situation seriously and work to keep the safety of our students, staff, and public a top priority.

We will open the schools from 11am to 6 pm on Wednesday, March 18, 2020 to pick up personal property and promptly leave. Hand sanitizer stations will be set up as you enter the building at the office doors. If you do not need to pick up items, please stay home. Items remaining in the building may be disposed of if we are unable to return prior to August.

Driver education is currently on hold until further notice. Please continue to watch your email for additional information.

It's National School Counseling Week 2020!
The week, which runs from Feb. 3-7, is sponsored by the American School Counselor Association (ASCA) and highlights the unique contribution of school counselors within U.S. school systems and the tremendous impact they can have in helping students achieve school success and plan for a career.

Take a moment to thank your local school counselor(s). Follow #NSCW2020 on social media.

To learn more about National School Counseling Week, visit www.schoolcounselor.org/nscw

We have had many cases and are still having cases of Influenza A& B going through the school. We have had some cases of strep throat. If you child is complaining of a sore throat, has a slight temp 99.5 or higher before school please keep them home. Your child needs to be fever free for 24 hours without any medication before returning to school.
Good ways to prevent the spread of infection/flu. GOOD HAND HYGIENE. Wash with warm soap and water. Cover mouth with elbow when coughing, Wash hands after blowing nose, before eating, after using the bathroom.

post_text:
Dear PAC Community,
This morning the district implemented its CRISIS plan to deal with reported threats that were brought to the district after school Thursday for the MS/HS. In consultation/coordination with Law Enforcement, two officers were placed in the school this morning, while two additional officers intercepted the student in question to assess if there was indeed a viable threat before school this morning. Law enforcement determined that there was no viable threat. We would like to thank the Pocahontas Police Department and Sheriff’s Office for their support. Please rest assured that the safety of our students and staff will remain our highest priority.

We would also like to express our appreciation to the students, parents, and staff who brought this concern to our attention. You are the reasons PAC is so special. Remember that PAC also offers Safe Schools Alert to report any concern to the district.

post_text:
Iowa is home to the largest high school dance team competition in the country. On Dec. 5 and 6 nearly 5000 high school and college students will compete at the 44th Annual Iowa State Dance Team Championships in Des Moines. The
Trendsetters will be among the 254 high school teams and twenty-four college teams that will make up the 600 routines that will be performed in a two-day period. Best of luck to the Trendsetters on Thursday!

post_text:
Illness is upon us all! A couple of things to remember:
1) WASH YOUR HANDS!! or USE HAND SANITIZER!! Before & After eating, After using the toilet, After blowing or touching your nose.
2) Cough and sneeze into your arm, not your hands!
3) Stay home if you have a fever of 100.5 or greater for at least 24 hours after it comes down to normal (98.6)
4) Do NOT come to school until 24 hours after the last time you've vomited. Stay home!
5) Do NOT come to school until 24 hours after the last time you've had diarrhea. Stay home!
6) If you have Strep throat, please stay home until 24 hours after your 1st dose of antibiotic.

Thank you and see you Friday and/or Saturday!
